      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/cou2/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation experiments must be conducted on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU. Operating conditions must span the full COU operating envelope. Blood analogue fluid properties must be within ±15% of physiological blood viscosity and density at 37 °C."
      },
      "rationale": "All validation experiments used the identical FDA generic pump geometry (CAD file SHA-256 hash verified against the COU simulation geometry). The five validation operating points bracket the full COU operating envelope from 3 to 8 L/min. The glycerol–water analogue (viscosity 3.5 mPa·s, density 1050 kg/m³) is within 6% of physiological blood viscosity and 0.5% of density, well within the ±15% tolerance."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/cou2/numerical-solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical solver error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Round-off error must be demonstrated to be negligible relative to discretization error. Double-precision arithmetic must be used throughout. Time-stepping for the steady-state MRF approach must demonstrate pseudo-time convergence with residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for all equations."
      },
      "rationale": "All simulations were executed in double-precision mode. A comparison of single- versus double-precision solutions on the 3.2 M cell grid confirmed that round-off differences in IH are below 0.01%, three orders of magnitude below the GCI discretization error. Pseudo-time convergence was achieved at residuals of 5×10⁻⁸ for continuity and momentum. No floating-point exceptions were recorded in solver logs."
    },
    {
